1
00:00:01,920 --> 00:00:05,371
1964年，全世界的目光都聚焦在日本——
In 1964, the eyes of the world were fixed on Japan

2
00:00:05,371 --> 00:00:08,200
东京奥运会盛大开幕。
as the Olympic Games kicked off in Tokyo.

3
00:00:08,800 --> 00:00:13,960
但真正抓住全球眼球的，不是奖牌，也不是盛典。
But, it wasn't the medals or parades that captured the world's attention.

4
00:00:13,960 --> 00:00:15,424
而是新干线——
It was the Shinkansen,

5
00:00:15,424 --> 00:00:17,553
一列划时代的高速列车，
a revolutionary high-speed train

6
00:00:17,553 --> 00:00:21,280
以破纪录的速度将乘客送往日本各地。
shooting passengers across the country at record speeds.

7
00:00:22,120 --> 00:00:27,000
这列子弹头列车，令全世界羡慕不已。
The bullet train was the envy of the world.

8
00:00:27,000 --> 00:00:32,840
它一声枪响，引燃了一场全球竞赛：谁能成为下一个跻身高铁俱乐部的国家？
Firing the starter pistol on a global race to be the next country to enter the high-speed club.

9
00:00:34,800 --> 00:00:37,360
跑在最前面的，是美国。
In pole position was the United States.

10
00:00:37,680 --> 00:00:40,876
凭借雄厚的技术实力和超级大国的资源，
With its technical prowess and superpower resources,

11
00:00:40,876 --> 00:00:43,027
一列纯美国血统的列车开始筹备——
work began on an all-American train

12
00:00:43,028 --> 00:00:45,732
目标是让新干线望尘莫及。
that would leave the Shinkansen in the dust.

13
00:00:45,732 --> 00:00:51,240
最高时速156英里（约251公里），几乎是当今最快列车的两倍。
Hitting a top speed of 156 mph, nearly double today's fastest speed.

14
00:00:51,640 --> 00:00:57,084
然而，子弹头列车在日本成了国家象征，60年过去了，
But, while the bullet train became a national icon in Japan, 60 years on,

15
00:00:57,084 --> 00:01:02,080
美国却仍在为建造第一条高铁线路苦苦挣扎。
the US is still struggling to build its first high-speed rail line.

16
00:01:02,720 --> 00:01:05,217
这是一个关于壮志未酬的故事，
This is a story of failed ambition,

17
00:01:05,217 --> 00:01:06,430
但它留下的遗产，
but with a legacy

18
00:01:06,430 --> 00:01:11,924
至今对美国铁路举足轻重。
that to this day remains of critical importance to rail in the United States.

19
00:01:11,924 --> 00:01:16,800
这就是美国尝试建造子弹头列车时所发生的一切。
This is what happens when America tried to build a bullet train.

20
00:01:25,520 --> 00:01:28,155
约翰逊总统向国会领袖们致以祝贺，
President Johnson has some words of congratulations

21
00:01:28,155 --> 00:01:29,447
感谢他们
for congressional leaders

22
00:01:29,447 --> 00:01:31,772
推动税收法案在两院顺利通过。
who spurred the tax bill through both houses.

23
00:01:31,772 --> 00:01:35,446
林登·B·约翰逊总统是一个有着宏大愿景的人。
President Lyndon B. Johnson was a man with a vision.

24
00:01:35,446 --> 00:01:37,982
1963年就任后，
When he took office in 1963,

25
00:01:37,982 --> 00:01:40,790
他立志将美国
he set out to transform America

26
00:01:40,790 --> 00:01:42,873
打造成"伟大社会"。
into the Great Society.

27
00:01:42,873 --> 00:01:44,747
他推行的一系列
The policies he introduced

28
00:01:44,747 --> 00:01:48,639
政策，旨在纠正美国社会各层面的积弊，
sought to right wrongs in every part of American life,

29
00:01:48,639 --> 00:01:50,080
交通运输也不例外。
including transport.

30
00:01:51,080 --> 00:01:57,688
美国开发出了举世无双的先进交通工具，
The US had developed the most technologically advanced vehicles in and out of the world,

31
00:01:57,688 --> 00:01:59,866
但有一个重大例外。
but with one major exception.

32
00:01:59,866 --> 00:02:05,178
>> >> 我们有飞行速度达到音速三倍的飞机。
>> >> We have airplanes which fly three times faster than sound.

33
00:02:05,452 --> 00:02:08,624
我们有绕火星运行的电视摄像机，
We have television cameras that are orbiting Mars,

34
00:02:08,624 --> 00:02:12,494
但城镇之间的大众交通，和30年前一样，
but we have the same tired and inadequate mass transportation

35
00:02:12,494 --> 00:02:15,920
依然陈旧落后，毫无长进。
between our towns and cities that we had 30 years ago.

36
00:02:16,400 --> 00:02:20,560
如果你没有汽车，在国内出行简直是一场折磨。
If you didn't have a car, getting around the country was a slog.

37
00:02:22,280 --> 00:02:26,608
更糟糕的是，仅仅20年前还是美国交战国的日本，
And to make it worse, Japan, a country the US was at war with

38
00:02:26,608 --> 00:02:32,000
如今凭借最新机车技术引领着世界。
just 20 years earlier, was now leading the world with its latest locomotive.

39
00:02:32,616 --> 00:02:38,640
>> [snorts] >> 子弹或许很快，但雄鹰更快。
>> [snorts] >> A bullet might be fast, but an eagle is faster.

40
00:02:39,200 --> 00:02:44,760
1965年，LBJ签署了《高速地面交通法案》。
In 1965, LBJ signed the High-Speed Ground Transportation Act.

41
00:02:44,960 --> 00:02:46,310
目标很简单：
Its goal was simple,

42
00:02:46,310 --> 00:02:48,740
支持美国高速铁路网络的
to back the research and development

43
00:02:48,740 --> 00:02:51,440
研究与开发。
of a high-speed train network in the US.

44
00:02:52,240 --> 00:02:57,480
其实，这并不是美国第一次涉足高铁领域。
Although this wasn't America's first foray into high-speed rail.

45
00:02:57,720 --> 00:03:00,664
让我们听听历史学家罗伯特·霍尔茨韦斯的讲述。
Here's historian Robert Holzweiss to tell us more.

46
00:03:00,664 --> 00:03:06,091
上世纪50年代末，纽约中央铁路在俄亥俄州搞了一个演示项目。
The New York Central Railroad in the late 1950s did a demonstration project in Ohio.

47
00:03:06,091 --> 00:03:08,498
他们把两台航空喷气发动机
It mounted two airline jet engines

48
00:03:08,498 --> 00:03:11,613
架在一节铁路柴油车（RDC）
on the top of what we call a rail diesel car

49
00:03:11,612 --> 00:03:12,320
的顶上。
or an RDC.

50
00:03:12,600 --> 00:03:14,440
就是一节普通的客车车厢。
It's just one passenger car.

51
00:03:14,680 --> 00:03:20,250
然后在一段笔直平坦的轨道上跑出了170多英里（约274公里）的时速。
And they went 170-something mph across a straight flat piece of track.

52
00:03:21,850 --> 00:03:25,188
测试地点是精心挑选的——
The area that was chosen to do this was purposely done.

53
00:03:25,188 --> 00:03:26,705
地势平坦笔直，
It was flat and straight,

54
00:03:26,705 --> 00:03:29,740
基础设施状况极佳。
and the infrastructure was in very good condition.

55
00:03:29,740 --> 00:03:30,660
我不认为
I don't think

56
00:03:30,660 --> 00:03:33,136
有人真的认真考虑过
there was any serious consideration

57
00:03:33,136 --> 00:03:34,905
把这个方案变成
of making these an actual

58
00:03:34,905 --> 00:03:37,027
实际的载客运输方式。
um way of transporting people.

59
00:03:37,027 --> 00:03:42,280
好在还有一些没那么疯狂的尝试，在推动高铁走向现实。
Fortunately, there were other less insane attempts to get high-speed rail up and running.

60
00:03:42,480 --> 00:03:45,000
克莱本·佩尔参议员登场了。
Enter Senator Claiborne Pell.

61
00:03:46,240 --> 00:03:49,960
1962年，他提出了"佩尔计划"。
In 1962, he had developed the Pell Plan.

62
00:03:50,480 --> 00:03:56,784
这一计划呼吁重振铁路网络，服务于东北走廊沿线高度密集的城市群——
It called for a revitalized rail network serving the highly dense cluster of cities

63
00:03:56,784 --> 00:04:02,480
也就是我们今天所说的东北走廊。
along the Northeast Corridor, a network we now call the Northeast Corridor.

64
00:04:02,720 --> 00:04:05,520
随着人们从城市涌向郊区，
As people moved from the cities to the suburbs,

65
00:04:05,520 --> 00:04:07,069
数以百万计的人开车上路，
millions took to the roads

66
00:04:07,068 --> 00:04:08,200
开启了通勤时代。
to begin commuting.

67
00:04:08,720 --> 00:04:13,027
但道路很快就堵死了，另一套解决方案迫在眉睫。
But, as those roads quickly clogged up, another solution was needed.

68
00:04:13,027 --> 00:04:17,099
州际公路对美国文化影响深远，
Interstate highways were a big impact on the US culture,

69
00:04:17,099 --> 00:04:19,280
我们本质上是一个汽车文化的国家。
and we were are a car culture.

70
00:04:19,519 --> 00:04:23,785
但发展大众交通的呼声，确实也在一步步向前推进。
And there was definitely a movement forward to get into more mass transportation.

71
00:04:23,785 --> 00:04:26,104
后来被称为东北走廊的这条线路，
What became known as the Northeast Corridor,

72
00:04:26,104 --> 00:04:28,212
当时归宾夕法尼亚铁路所有，
then owned by the Pennsylvania Railroad,

73
00:04:28,212 --> 00:04:29,688
成了最理想的改造目标。
was a prime target for that.

74
00:04:30,128 --> 00:04:33,669
这条线路早已实现电气化——自1930年代起便是如此，
It was already electrified, had been since 1930s,

75
00:04:33,669 --> 00:04:39,883
非常适合进一步发展为连接美国经济首都纽约
and it was ripe for further development into a more high-speed transportation corridor

76
00:04:39,883 --> 00:04:43,424
与政治首都华盛顿特区的高速交通走廊。
between the economic capital of the US, New York,

77
00:04:43,424 --> 00:04:46,531
与政治首都华盛顿特区的高速交通走廊。
and the political capital, Washington, D.C.

78
00:04:46,531 --> 00:04:49,832
随着约翰逊高铁梦逐渐成形，
As Johnson's high-speed dream began to take shape,

79
00:04:49,832 --> 00:04:51,219
它最终落地为
it did so in the form

80
00:04:51,219 --> 00:04:54,520
佩尔参议员针对东北走廊提出的方案。
of Senator Pell's plan for the Northeast Corridor.

81
00:04:54,960 --> 00:04:57,560
该法案资助了两个试点项目。
The bill sponsored two test projects.

82
00:04:58,520 --> 00:05:01,800
第一个就是这列——巴德公司涡轮列车（Turbo Train）。
The first was this, the Turbo train.

83
00:05:02,240 --> 00:05:05,779
采用电力驱动加柴油涡轮引擎，
Using an electric engine and a diesel-powered turbine,

84
00:05:05,779 --> 00:05:07,679
运行于纽约
it would run between New York

85
00:05:07,679 --> 00:05:08,400
与波士顿之间。
and Boston.

86
00:05:09,000 --> 00:05:13,579
第二个方案服务于至关重要的纽约至华盛顿路线，
The second scheme would serve the crucial New York to Washington route,

87
00:05:13,579 --> 00:05:14,546
而正是这个方案，
and it was this

88
00:05:14,546 --> 00:05:18,480
对美国铁路产生了最为深远的影响。
that would go on to have the most lasting impacts on US rail.

89
00:05:20,400 --> 00:05:23,952
好了，说到这个故事，我们得回到那个遥远的年代——
Now, we're going way back into the mists of time with this story

90
00:05:23,952 --> 00:05:26,893
那时候，人们只能用极为原始的技术工作。
when they had to work with very primitive technology.

91
00:05:26,893 --> 00:05:28,702
我这儿就有个例子。
I have an example of it here.

92
00:05:28,702 --> 00:05:31,200
叫做纸和笔。
It's called pen and paper.

93
00:05:31,680 --> 00:05:34,100
这是我从当地博物馆借来的，
I borrowed these from a local museum,

94
00:05:34,100 --> 00:05:35,604
但没人真的知道
but no one really knows

95
00:05:35,604 --> 00:05:36,520
怎么用。
how they work.

96
00:05:36,520 --> 00:05:38,850
好在，在今天这个开明的时代，
Fortunately, in today's enlightened age,

97
00:05:38,850 --> 00:05:41,122
我们可以依赖更先进的技术，
we can rely on more advanced technology

98
00:05:41,123 --> 00:05:41,880
比如Odoo。
such as Odoo.

99
00:05:41,880 --> 00:05:44,734
Odoo是一个一体化的企业管理平台，
Odoo is an all-in-one business management platform

100
00:05:44,734 --> 00:05:47,988
把经营企业中所有繁琐的事务
that takes all the painful stuff about running a business

101
00:05:47,988 --> 00:05:49,244
都化繁为简。
and makes it a breeze.

102
00:05:49,244 --> 00:05:51,186
别说建一条新铁路了，光是运营B1M就有一大堆后台工作：
Forget building a new railway,

103
00:05:51,186 --> 00:05:54,618
追收款、签合同、排人手、管HR，诸如此类。
running the B1M comes with a ton of back office work,

104
00:05:54,618 --> 00:05:59,474
追收款、签合同、排人手、管HR，诸如此类。
chasing invoices, signing contracts, scheduling resources, HR, you name it.

105
00:05:59,474 --> 00:06:02,150
但现在这些我都能在Odoo里一站式搞定，
But, now I can do all of that within Odoo

106
00:06:02,150 --> 00:06:07,372
因为他们把45个应用整合进了一个高效的生态系统。
because they've taken 45 apps and brought them all into one efficient ecosystem.

107
00:06:07,492 --> 00:06:09,802
各模块无缝联通，
Everything communicates seamlessly,

108
00:06:09,802 --> 00:06:12,376
Odoo甚至能自动处理那些看似微不足道的手动任务——
and Odoo can even automate manual tasks

109
00:06:12,377 --> 00:06:16,866
直到你在复制数据时少打了个零，
that seem trivial until you miss a zero off when copying data across

110
00:06:16,866 --> 00:06:19,440
然后一切就彻底脱轨。
and then everything goes off the rails.

111
00:06:19,440 --> 00:06:22,469
你可以根据自身需求量身定制，
You can tailor everything to your specific needs,

112
00:06:22,469 --> 00:06:23,644
而且扩展性很强。
plus it's scalable.

113
00:06:23,644 --> 00:06:27,567
所以你可以从小处起步，随着业务增长再逐步添加应用。
So, you can start off small and add apps as your business grows.

114
00:06:27,567 --> 00:06:31,726
最棒的是，你的第一个应用完全免费，终身使用，
But, the best part is that your first app is completely free for life,

115
00:06:31,726 --> 00:06:33,805
还包含无限技术支持
and that includes unlimited support

116
00:06:33,805 --> 00:06:34,518
和托管服务。
and hosting.

117
00:06:34,518 --> 00:06:37,645
你所要做的，就是选好第一个应用，上手试试。
All you got to do is choose your first app and give it a try.

118
00:06:37,645 --> 00:06:40,005
扫描屏幕上的二维码，
You can do that by scanning the QR code on screen

119
00:06:40,005 --> 00:06:41,883
或点击简介中的链接，
or clicking the link in the description

120
00:06:41,883 --> 00:06:42,894
今天就开始吧。
to get started today.

121
00:06:42,894 --> 00:06:51,320
好了，你们继续看视频，我来研究研究这玩意儿怎么用。
Now, I'm going to let you guys watch the rest of the video while I'll figure out what to do with this.

122
00:06:52,560 --> 00:06:54,805
如果你要建一条高铁线路，
Now, if you're building a high-speed rail line,

123
00:06:54,805 --> 00:06:55,856
有几个关键因素
there are a few things

124
00:06:55,855 --> 00:06:57,670
必须考虑周全。
you've got to take into consideration.

125
00:06:57,670 --> 00:07:03,438
首先，速度越快，任何颠簸和震动都会被成倍放大，
First off, traveling fast means you'll feel any bump or jolt far more than lower speeds.

126
00:07:03,438 --> 00:07:06,322
所以轨道必须焊接固定，
So, your track needs to be welded into place

127
00:07:06,322 --> 00:07:10,320
防止列车和乘客被震得七零八落。
to stop the trains and the passengers being shaken to pieces.

128
00:07:11,200 --> 00:07:17,000
列车碾过钢轨接缝时那种熟悉的"咔嗒"声，将彻底消失。
That familiar click-clack sounds as the train passes over different sets of rails is gone.

129
00:07:17,800 --> 00:07:21,520
其次，要尽可能减少一切降速因素。
Secondly, you want as few things to slow you down as possible.

130
00:07:22,000 --> 00:07:23,949
排在首位的就是弯道。
Top of that list are corners.

131
00:07:23,949 --> 00:07:25,696
沿线每一处曲线
Any curves along the route

132
00:07:25,696 --> 00:07:28,720
都必须尽量平缓、舒展。
need to be as shallow and gentle as possible.

133
00:07:29,320 --> 00:07:34,935
高速过弯时，离心力会将列车向外甩。
Going round a corner at high speed means the centrifugal force will throw the train outwards.

134
00:07:34,935 --> 00:07:38,473
因此，轨道的倾角——即轨道超高——必须相应抬高，
So, the angle or can't of the track needs to be raised

135
00:07:38,473 --> 00:07:41,160
以平衡作用在钢轨上的载荷。
to balance the load applied on the rails.

136
00:07:42,760 --> 00:07:46,240
最后，还需要稳定可靠的电力供应。
Finally, you'll also need a reliable power supply.

137
00:07:46,365 --> 00:07:51,040
>> >> 对于电力列车，电能由头顶的架空导线提供，这套系统叫做接触网。
>> >> For electric trains, that's supplied by the overhead wires known as a catenary.

138
00:07:52,240 --> 00:07:58,520
高速行驶时，受电弓会发生抖动，与导线失去接触。
At high speeds, the pantograph would bounce and lose contact with the wire.

139
00:07:58,680 --> 00:08:02,954
所以他们不得不改变导线的架设方式，
And so, they had to change the way the the wire was strung,

140
00:08:02,954 --> 00:08:07,445
同时也改变了受电弓的工作方式——
and they uh also had to change the way the pantograph operated

141
00:08:07,445 --> 00:08:10,849
从原来的三角形结构改为V形，
from a sort of a triangular shape to a V-shape,

142
00:08:10,849 --> 00:08:15,602
以保持张力，确保受电弓始终与导线紧密接触。
and to keep tension on it and keep it in contact with the wire.

143
00:08:15,601 --> 00:08:19,474
1966年，一段21英里长的试验轨道
In 1966, work began on upgrading a 21-mile stretch of track

144
00:08:19,474 --> 00:08:22,231
开始升级改造，用于在整条线路完工前对首批车厢
which would be used to test the first cars

145
00:08:22,231 --> 00:08:25,053
进行测试。
before work on the whole line was complete.

146
00:08:25,733 --> 00:08:28,783
测试区选在新泽西州，
The test area was was going to be in New Jersey,

147
00:08:28,783 --> 00:08:33,167
那里早已有大量平直轨道，
where it was already a significant amount of flat and straight track,

148
00:08:33,167 --> 00:08:37,805
与十年前纽约中央铁路在俄亥俄州所选条件如出一辙。
just like in the Ohio example with the New York Central a decade earlier.

149
00:08:37,804 --> 00:08:41,142
